        <h2 class="section-header">Your Cat's Diet</h2>
        <p>
          Becoming a cat owner for the first time can be an exciting yet
          overwhelming experience. One of the key aspects to focus on is your
          cat's dietary needs. Cats are carnivores and their diet should be rich
          in animal protein. It's crucial to choose a high-quality food that is
          appropriate for their age and lifestyle, as nutritional needs can
          vary.
        </p>
        <p>
          For instance, kittens have different nutritional requirements compared
          to adult cats. Both wet and dry foods have their benefits. Wet food
          aids in hydration but can't be left out for long, while dry food is
          easier to store and promotes dental hygiene.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you decide to change your cat's diet, do it gradually over a week
          to avoid upsetting their stomach. Also, cats prefer their water and
          food sources to be separate, mimicking their natural behavior to avoid
          contamination.
        </p>
        <p>
          Lastly, remember that cats are excellent at conserving water, so don't
          be alarmed if you don't see your cat drinking much, especially if
          they're on a wet food diet.
        </p>
